******
[1]
Date: Mon 8 Oct 2012
Source: prensa-latina.cu [in Italian, machine transl., edited]
http://www.prensa-latina.cu/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=594231&Itemid=5


A meningitis outbreak spread to 4 of the nearly 3000 people aboard the MSC Orchestra cruise [ship], which docked yesterday [7 Oct 2012] in an Italian port, said local authorities. According to the source, the 2800 passengers on the boat had to be treated [urgently] against disease, after 4 crew members were hospitalized in serious condition.

One of the patients, a 32 year old Indonesian citizen, was reported to be very seriously ill by the head of emergency medicine at the hospital in Livorno, Francesco Genovesi, where a 47 year old Italian who worked in the ship's galley was also transferred. The other 2 infected people, a Brazilian and a Filipino, were admitted to the infectious diseases section of the hospital.

In a statement issued on Monday [8 Oct 2012] by MSC Cruises reported that "as a precaution and according to maritime authorities, all passengers received antibiotic prophylaxis. No other member of the crew or passengers showed symptoms of meningitis." The alarm about the spread had been given on Sunday [7 Oct 2012], when the MSC Orchestra arrived in Livorno (west of Italy), and since continued its journey to the French town of Villefranche, where another tour will to begin. The shipping company said that health authorities provided maritime antibiotic prophylaxis "just a precaution" and that the ship sailed after receiving clearance from doctors.

According to several media outlets say, the incident is another blow to the cruise industry, after 32 people died last January during the sinking of the Costa Crociere along the Tuscan coast.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail rapporteur Mary Marshall

******
[2]
Date: Mon 8 Oct 2012
Source: cruiselawnews.com [edited]
http://www.cruiselawnews.com/2012/10/articles/crew-member-rights-1/crew-members-aboard-msc-orchestra-stricken-with-meningitis/


A newspaper in Italy [http://www.ansa.it/web/notizie/rubriche/cronaca/2012/10/07/Meningite-nave-quattro-casi-sospetti-_7592928.html] is reporting that 4 crew members of the cruise ship MSC Orchestra have contracted bacterial meningitis. 2 of the 4 crew members are considered to be in serious condition. They were all hospitalized once the cruise ship reached port yesterday [7 Oct 2012].

According to this newspaper, one crew member is a 32 year old Indonesian who is currently in septic shock in the intensive care unit of a hospital in Livorno, Italy. He apparently worked in the engine room. A 2nd crew member is a 47 year old Italian who works in the cruise ship's galley, who also is in the intensive care unit. 2 other crew members include a Brazilian and a Filipino, whose conditions are described as less serious. They are hospitalized in the hospital's infectious disease department.

Other newspapers [http://www.abc.es/20121008/local-comunidad-valenciana/abci-cuatro-miembros-tripulacion-crucero-201210081422.html] state that the serious cases involve an Indonesian, age 32, and a Filipino, age 30, both of whom worked in the engine room.

Meningitis is an infection of the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. Bacterial meningitis is very serious and can be fatal. It is not common on cruise ships, although it has occurred on other cruise ships [http://www.nzherald.co.nz/world/news/article.cfm?c_id=2&objectid=10670158] as this case illustrates.

All of the crew members were given prophylactic antibiotics, which were also offered to the passengers. The 2800 dosages were described as an "unprecedented quantity over a period of time so limited." The medicine consisted of an antibiotic tablet of 500 milligrams for adults and syrup for about 400 children who were on board. An epidemiological survey was also conducted among the crew members who in recent days have been most in contact with the hospitalized crew.

The Orchestra is continuing its cruise as planned and has meanwhile docked in France's Villafranche, with next stops including Valencia, Ibiza, Tunis, Catania and Naples.

