******
[3]
Date: Tue 9 Oct 2012
Source: ubalert.com [edited]
http://www.ubalert.com/0o2?open_ctab=1


The Italian Health Ministry reported on Monday [8 Oct 2012] that passengers on board an Italian cruise ship were given antibiotics after 4 of the ship's crew members were found to have bacterial meningitis. The ministry said that all 4 had been transported to hospitals in the port of Livorno. Doctors have distributed more than 2800 doses of rifampicin and ciprofloxacin to passengers of the MSC Orchestra. Those who had already disembarked over the past week are advised to take similar precautionary measures. The 2500 passenger cruise ship is now anchored in the port of Villefranche sur Mer in France.

Italian officials have already contacted their French counterparts. The cruise company stated that it was doing all that is necessary to ensure the health and well-being of its crew members and guests. The 4 crew members were found to have contracted meningococcal meningitis. The illness is transmitted through close contact with saliva or respiratory secretions. The Health Ministry also noted that the strain was detected in crew members working in the ship's kitchen; hence, it is not likely that they had close contact with guests. 2 out of the 4 cases were diagnosed as [meningitis due to _Neisseria meningitidis_ serogroup] C.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the United States and most industrialized countries, antibiotic chemoprophylaxis among close contacts of a patient with invasive meningococcal disease is recommended to prevent secondary cases.

The following is extracted from moderator ML's comments in ProMED-mail post Meningitis, bacterial, airplane exposure - USA (KS ex FL): alert 20070724.2378:

Meningococcal meningitis occurs sporadically or as epidemics. Certain types of close contact of a case of meningococcal meningitis place a person at increased risk of developing meningitis for which antimicrobial chemoprophylaxis is recommended. These contacts include household members, daycare center members, and anyone directly exposed to the patient's respiratory secretions (for example, by kissing, mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, or intubation of the patient) [see:
http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00046263.htm].

Antibiotics recommended for chemoprophylaxis are rifampin (an oral dose administered twice daily for 2 days), ciprofloxacin (single oral dose), and ceftriaxone (a single intramuscular dose). Chemoprophylaxis is not recommended for school or work contacts not directly exposed to directly exposed to a patient's respiratory secretions (<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5945a2.htm).

According to CDC, for management of passengers aboard an airplane exposed to meningococcal disease, household members traveling with the index patient as well as persons traveling with the index patient who have prolonged close contact (for example, roommates, members of the same sports team) should be identified and the need for antimicrobial chemoprophylaxis evaluated. Antimicrobial chemoprophylaxis should also be considered for airline passengers who have had direct contact with respiratory secretions from the index patient, and for passengers seated directly next to the index patient on prolonged flights (>8 hours)
(http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2012/chapter-6-conveyance-and-transportation-issues/air-travel.htm).

Because the risk for illness is highest during the first few days after infection, chemoprophylaxis should be administered as soon as possible (ideally within 24 hours) after contact with an index case-patient
(http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/mm5023a2.htm).

Chemoprophylaxis administered >14 days is probably of limited or no value. For both the meningococcal conjugate and the polysaccharide vaccines, at least 7-10 days are required following vaccination for development of immunity. Meningococcal vaccination, however, is used to control spread of meningitis in outbreak situations.

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be found at http://healthmap.org/r/1BIF. - Mod.ML]
